    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Working People Springsteen Doesn't Understand'' (Op-Ed, June 17):</p>
        <p>I was distressed to read Lt. George Mole's interpretation of and response to Bruce Springsteen's song ''American Skin.'' Politicizing an artistic portrayal of Amadou Diallo's death is far beneath the dignity of a member of the New York City Police Department.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Working People Springsteen Doesn't Understand'' (Op-Ed, June 17):</p>
        <p>I was distressed to read Lt. George Mole's interpretation of and response to Bruce Springsteen's song ''American Skin.'' Politicizing an artistic portrayal of Amadou Diallo's death is far beneath the dignity of a member of the New York City Police Department.</p>
        <p>Because we depend on the police to respond immediately to life-or-death situations, forgiveness is warranted even when innocent mistakes become tragic. But this forgiveness should not excuse the same kind of reflexive behavior when it tries to pass for cultural criticism.</p>
        <p>Certainly, Mr. Springsteen's poignant song touches a raw nerve. But Lieutenant Mole's view that the song either accuses, implies or demonstrates contempt is at odds with its content. It is simply a sympathetic overture to the memory of a man who was killed.</p>
        <p>DAVID HEIDE  New York, June 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
